  <h1>Types of Severance Pay</h1>
  <p class="byline">Reviewed by <strong>Sloan Whitfield, SHRM-CP</strong> &mdash; Editor-in-Chief &amp; Separation Agreements Lead. Updated May 2026.</p>

  <p>
    Not all severance arrangements are alike. The type of package you receive — or can negotiate — depends on the circumstances of your departure, your level, your industry, and whether your employer is legally required to provide anything at all. Understanding the different categories of severance helps you recognize what you're being offered, what's missing, and what you might reasonably push for.
  </p>

  <h2>Standard Formula-Based Severance</h2>
  <p>
    The most common arrangement in mid-size and large U.S. companies, formula-based severance ties the payout directly to tenure and salary. The typical benchmark is <strong>one to two weeks of base pay per year of service</strong>, sometimes subject to a floor (e.g., a minimum of two weeks regardless of tenure) and a cap (e.g., no more than 26 weeks). This formula is usually codified in a company's written severance policy or in an offer letter.
  </p>
  <p>
    Formula-based severance is often non-negotiable for hourly or entry-level roles, but may serve as a starting point for negotiation at the manager and director level. Employees should check whether their employer's policy distinguishes between layoffs, RIFs, and other separation types — some employers only pay formula severance in the case of an involuntary, non-performance-related termination.
  </p>

  <h2>Enhanced Negotiated Packages</h2>
  <p>
    For exempt employees, mid-to-senior managers, and executives, severance is frequently negotiated above the formula baseline. Enhanced packages may include accelerated equity vesting, extended health benefits, continued bonus eligibility for the payout period, and outplacement services. In practice, the more leverage the employee has — specialized skills, institutional knowledge, potential legal claims — the larger the enhancement tends to be.
  </p>
  <p>
    When negotiating an enhanced package, the key is to make specific, documented requests rather than broad demands. Asking for an extension of COBRA subsidy from three months to six months, or for vesting acceleration on unvested RSUs that were scheduled to vest within the next 90 days, is far more effective than simply asking for "more." Use the calculator on our homepage to anchor your ask to real benchmarks.
  </p>

  <h2>WARN Act Statutory Severance</h2>
  <p>
    The Worker Adjustment and Retraining Notification Act (WARN Act) requires employers with 100 or more full-time employees to give 60 calendar days' advance notice before a mass layoff or plant closing. If the employer fails to provide proper notice, affected employees are entitled to <strong>back pay and benefits for each day of the violation, up to 60 days</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    WARN Act back pay is not traditional severance — it is a statutory remedy for inadequate notice. But in practice, many employees receive both: a company may pay WARN Act liability in lieu of the 60-day notice period and then layer a separate severance package on top. Some states (California, New York, Illinois, New Jersey) have their own "mini-WARN" laws with lower employee thresholds and broader coverage.
  </p>

  <h2>Garden Leave</h2>
  <p>
    Garden leave is an arrangement in which an employee is told their services are no longer required but remains on the payroll — and technically still employed — through the end of their notice period. During garden leave, the employee typically is not expected to work, cannot start new employment, and may be prohibited from accessing company systems or contacting clients. It is more common in the UK and in U.S. financial services roles where immediate access to competitors must be prevented.
  </p>
  <p>
    From the employee's perspective, garden leave is generally favorable: you continue to accumulate benefits, retirement contributions, and sometimes unvested equity while being paid not to work. The downside is the restriction on new employment, which can range from weeks to several months.
  </p>

  <h2>Payment in Lieu of Notice (PILON)</h2>
  <p>
    A PILON arrangement pays out the cash value of the contractual or statutory notice period as a lump sum instead of keeping the employee on the payroll. This is common when an employer wants an immediate clean break — particularly in sensitive roles where access to confidential information is a concern. Unlike garden leave, a PILON employee is no longer employed from the date of termination, which means benefit accrual stops immediately.
  </p>
  <p>
    PILON arrangements require careful review: the lump sum may be taxed differently depending on whether it is classified as "wages" or as damages for breach of the notice provision. An employment attorney can advise on the tax treatment and whether the PILON calculation correctly reflects all owed compensation including benefits.
  </p>

  <h2>Executive Separation Agreements</h2>
  <p>
    C-suite and senior vice president-level separations typically involve individually negotiated separation agreements drafted by employment counsel on both sides. These agreements often include: a cash severance of six months to two years of base salary; a prorated or full annual bonus; extended vesting for equity awards; non-compete clauses with defined geographic and functional scope; and long-term consulting arrangements that provide continued income while technically respecting a non-compete.
  </p>
  <p>
    Executive packages are usually subject to IRC Section 409A (deferred compensation rules) and Section 280G (golden parachute excise tax) considerations. Payments structured as installments rather than lump sums can affect both the tax treatment and the employer's ability to recover ("clawback") compensation if subsequent breaches are discovered.
  </p>

  <h2>Mutual Separation Agreements</h2>
  <p>
    Sometimes called a "voluntary separation" or "separation by mutual agreement," this type of departure is presented as consensual but is often employer-initiated. The employer offers a package in exchange for the employee's agreement to resign, waive claims, and maintain confidentiality. Mutual separations are common in restructurings where the employer wants to avoid characterizing the separation as a layoff for HR reporting purposes.
  </p>
  <p>
    Employees should treat mutual separation offers with the same scrutiny as any layoff package. The fact that it is labeled "mutual" does not mean you have less leverage — in some cases, more, because the employer is avoiding the optics of a forced termination. Review the waiver of claims carefully; ensure you understand exactly what rights you are giving up.
  </p>

  <h2>Performance-Based Separation</h2>
  <p>
    When an employee is separated for performance reasons, severance is not legally required, and many employers offer little or nothing. However, some companies do offer a modest package — often one week per year of service — to reduce the risk of litigation and protect their employer brand. Employees in this category should still review their offer letter, employment contract, and any company severance policy to confirm whether they are entitled to any payment.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you believe you were actually laid off for business reasons but the departure was characterized as performance-related to avoid severance obligations, consult an employment attorney. Misclassification of separation type is not uncommon and may be actionable.
  </p>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    This page provides general educational information and is not legal advice. Severance entitlements depend on your specific situation, employment agreement, and applicable state and federal law. Consult a licensed employment attorney for guidance on your individual circumstances.
  </p>
